---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const title = "BC PNP Points Calculator Guide 2026: How to Increase Your Score";
const description = "Ultimate guide to the BC PNP Skills Immigration Registration System (SIRS). Learn how points are calculated for wage, education, and language, and 5 ways to increase your score.";
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <article class="min-h-screen bg-slate-50 py-12 px-4 sm:px-6">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto space-y-8">
      
      <!-- Header -->
      <header class="space-y-4 text-center">
        <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-black text-slate-900 tracking-tight leading-tight">
          Master the <span class="text-red-600">BC PNP Points</span> System
        </h1>
        <p class="text-lg text-slate-600 max-w-2xl mx-auto leading-relaxed">
          The Skills Immigration Registration System (SIRS) is competitive. This guide reveals exactly how to maximize your 200 points in 2025.
        </p>
      </header>

      <!-- Main Content -->
      <div class="prose prose-lg prose-slate max-w-none bg-white p-8 sm:p-12 rounded-[2rem] border border-slate-100 shadow-sm">
        
        <h2>How Scoring Works (200 Points Total)</h2>
        <p>
            Your score is divided into two main categories: <strong>Human Capital</strong> (what you bring) and <strong>Economic Factors</strong> (your job offer).
        </p>

        <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-8 my-8 not-prose">
            <div>
                <h3 class="font-black text-slate-900 text-xl mb-4 border-b border-slate-100 pb-2">Human Capital (120 pts)</h3>
                <ul class="space-y-3 text-slate-600 text-sm">
                    <li class="flex justify-between">
                        <span>Directly Related Experience</span>
                        <span class="font-bold">40 pts</span>
                    </li>
                     <li class="flex justify-between">
                        <span>Education Level</span>
                        <span class="font-bold">40 pts</span>
                    </li>
                     <li class="flex justify-between">
                        <span>Language Ability (CLB)</span>
                        <span class="font-bold">40 pts</span>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </div>
             <div>
                <h3 class="font-black text-slate-900 text-xl mb-4 border-b border-slate-100 pb-2">Economic Factors (80 pts)</h3>
                <ul class="space-y-3 text-slate-600 text-sm">
                    <li class="flex justify-between">
                        <span>Hourly Wage of Offer</span>
                        <span class="font-bold">55 pts</span>
                    </li>
                     <li class="flex justify-between">
                        <span>Area of Employment</span>
                        <span class="font-bold">25 pts</span>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>

        <h2>Top 5 Ways to Increase Your Score</h2>
        
        <h3>1. Negotiate a Higher Wage</h3>
        <p>
            This is the single biggest "swing" factor. Points are awarded for every dollar increase up to $70/hr. Even a $2/hr raise can sometimes add critical points.
        </p>

        <h3>2. Move Outside Metro Vancouver</h3>
        <p>
            The B.C. government wants people in regional areas.
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Metro Vancouver:</strong> 0 points for location.</li>
            <li><strong>Squamish/Abbotsford:</strong> 5 points.</li>
            <li><strong>Far North/Interior:</strong> Up to 15-25 points (depending on regional experience bonuses).</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>3. Retake Your Language Test</h3>
        <p>
            The difference between CLB 7 and CLB 9 is huge (+10 points). If you are stuck at CLB 7, investing in an IELTS tutor to reach CLB 9 is one of the cheapest ways to gain points.
        </p>

        <h3>4. Gain 1 Year of Canadian Experience</h3>
        <p>
            You get bonus points for having at least 1 year of experience <em>in Canada</em>. If you are close, waiting a few months to hit that 1-year mark might trigger the bonus.
        </p>
        
        <h3>5. Secure a Professional Designation</h3>
        <p>
            If you work in trades or certified professions, having your valid B.C. certification adds points to your Education score.
        </p>

        <h2>Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Overclaiming Experience:</strong> Only claim "Directly Related" experience. If the officer decides your past job isn't relevant, they act like it doesn't exist, causing your score to plummet and your application to be refused.</li>
            <li><strong>Including Bonuses in Wage:</strong> Only your guaranteed base hourly rate counts. Do not include overtime, tips, or annual bonuses in your calculation.</li>
        </ul>

        <hr class="my-8 border-slate-100" />

        <h2>BC PNP Cut Off Scores (Recent History)</h2>
        <p>
            Understanding the BC PNP cut off score trends helps you know if you are competitive. Here are typical ranges by stream:
        </p>
        <div class="not-prose overflow-x-auto my-6">
            <table class="min-w-full text-left text-sm">
                <thead class="bg-slate-50 border-b border-slate-200">
                    <tr>
                        <th class="px-4 py-3 font-bold">Stream</th>
                        <th class="px-4 py-3 font-bold">Typical Cut-Off</th>
                        <th class="px-4 py-3 font-bold">Lowest Seen</th>
                    </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody class="divide-y divide-slate-100">
                    <tr>
                        <td class="px-4 py-3">Skilled Worker (General)</td>
                        <td class="px-4 py-3">115-130 points</td>
                        <td class="px-4 py-3">105 points</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td class="px-4 py-3">BC PNP Tech</td>
                        <td class="px-4 py-3">100-115 points</td>
                        <td class="px-4 py-3">85 points</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td class="px-4 py-3">Healthcare</td>
                        <td class="px-4 py-3">90-105 points</td>
                        <td class="px-4 py-3">60 points</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td class="px-4 py-3">International Graduate</td>
                        <td class="px-4 py-3">100-120 points</td>
                        <td class="px-4 py-3">95 points</td>
                    </tr>
                </tbody>
            </table>
        </div>
        <p>
            Check the <a href="/bc-pnp-draws">latest BC PNP draw results</a> for the most current cut-off scores.
        </p>

        <h2>BC PNP Score Chart Breakdown</h2>
        <p>
            Here is how the BC PNP scoring system allocates the maximum 200 points:
        </p>
        <div class="not-prose grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2 my-6">
            <div class="bg-red-50 p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-100">
                <h4 class="font-bold text-red-900 mb-2">Wage (55 pts max)</h4>
                <p class="text-sm text-red-800">The largest single factor. $25/hr = ~20 pts, $50/hr = ~40 pts, $70+/hr = 55 pts.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-blue-50 p-4 rounded-xl border border-blue-100">
                <h4 class="font-bold text-blue-900 mb-2">Experience (40 pts max)</h4>
                <p class="text-sm text-blue-800">5+ years directly related = 40 pts. Canadian experience adds bonus.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-green-50 p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-100">
                <h4 class="font-bold text-green-900 mb-2">Education (40 pts max)</h4>
                <p class="text-sm text-green-800">PhD/Masters = 34-40 pts. Bachelor's = 28 pts. Trade cert = 22 pts.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-purple-50 p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-100">
                <h4 class="font-bold text-purple-900 mb-2">Language (40 pts max)</h4>
                <p class="text-sm text-purple-800">CLB 9+ = 30-40 pts. CLB 7 = 20 pts. CLB 4 = 10 pts.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

      </div>
      
      <!-- CTA -->
      <div class="bg-slate-900 rounded-[2rem] p-8 sm:p-12 text-center text-white">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-black mb-4">Ready to Calculate?</h2>
        <p class="text-slate-300 mb-8 max-w-xl mx-auto">
           Use our official calculator to see your exact score based on these rules.
        </p>
        <a href="/bc-pnp-calculator" class="inline-flex items-center bg-red-600 hover:bg-red-700 text-white px-8 py-4 rounded-full font-bold uppercase tracking-widest transition-all shadow-lg shadow-red-900/50">
            Start Calculator
        </a>
      </div>

    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
